{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"857b4353-d520-4426-bb43-6dbd23941a5c","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Here's the working output:\n\n```\nSpan<nint>:  [0, 10, 20, 30]\nSpan<nuint>: [0, 20, 40, 60]\nnint size:   8 bytes\n```\n\nThe syntax is straightforward:\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[4];\nSpan<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[4];\n```\n\nNo `unsafe` context is needed — assigning `stackalloc` directly to a `Span<T>` is safe. This works because `nint`/`nuint` are unmanaged types, which is the only requirement for `stackalloc`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1ecc7268-f961-4766-8024-8cd3526eaf38","outputTokens":203,"requestId":"E3C6:3A80DA:1C9BF22:2035492:6A07C218"},"id":"1bdd171d-d87b-4ba2-aeb8-f7d95ec5a51d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:21.784Z","parentId":"32dfba8c-b3cb-481f-b56c-addee82a4af9"}
